 are understood as relational beings, parents are recognized as people with needs and hopes and families as carrying extraordinary capacities for care and protection. The authors, who have over three decades of experience as social workers, managers, educators and researchers in England, also identify the key ingredients of just organizational cultures where learning is celebrated. This important book will be required reading for students on qualifying and post-qualifying courses in child protection, social workers, managers, academics and policy makers.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Mrz 2024) 0aChild welfarezGreat Britain. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Social Work.2bisacsh1 aMorris, Kate, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aWhite, Susan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBristol UP/Policy Press Complete eBook-Package 2014z9783111196343oZDB-23-BUPP0 cprintz978144730801040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781447308034423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781447308034/original  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-BUPPb2014